59    /**
60    * A parser for the Manchester OWL Syntax. All properties must be defined before
61    * they are used. For example, consider the restriction hasPart some Leg. The
62    * parser must know in advance whether or not hasPart is an object property or a
63    * data property so that Leg gets parsed correctly. In a tool, such as an
64    * editor, it is expected that hasPart will already exists as either a data
65    * property or an object property. If a complete ontology is being parsed, it is
66    * expected that hasPart will have been defined at the top of the file before it
67    * is used in any class expressions or property assertions (e.g. ObjectProperty:
68    * hasPart)
69    *
70    * @author Matthew Horridge, The University Of Manchester, Bio-Health
71    * Informatics Group
72    * @since 2.2.0
73    */
 
67% Uncovered Elements: 766 (2,318) Complexity: 529 Complexity Density: 0.36
74    public class ManchesterOWLSyntaxParserImpl implements
75    ManchesterOWLSyntaxParser {
76   
77    // This parser was built by hand! After struggling with terrible
78    // error messages produced by ANTLR (or JavaCC) I decides to construct
